    {
      "id": "note_37",
      "text": "Pearson's chi-squared test in two modes. Independence: cross-tabulate two categorical columns into a contingency table and test whether the two variables are associated (Yates' continuity correction is applied to 2×2 tables). Goodness-of-fit: take one column and test whether its category counts (or the raw counts, if numeric) depart from a uniform expectation. Reports the statistic, degrees of freedom and p-value, and shows the table in the node. It warns when expected cell counts fall below 5, where the χ² approximation breaks down (prefer Fisher's exact test). Matches scipy (chisquare / chi2_contingency). Pearson 1900.",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
